In presenting his arguments Gentili shows a thorough ac· quaintance with the facts in the case and with the principles which underlie it. He has a logical mind and his method of argumentation is keen. Sometimes, indeed, his shrewdness is carried so lar that his reasoning lacks the note ol sincerity. In attempting an appreciation ol the literary torm oi his pleas, it is only fair to bear in mind two consideratione He was ad· dressing a seventeenth not a twentieth century court, and he did not see this book through the press. Gentili was a very learned man, and not only the weight but the actual number oi authorities which an advocate cited counted heavily in the mind ol a judge. It was natural, therefore, ior Gentili, out of his wide reading, to multiply references to earlier jurists. It is not im· possible too that he may have felt a pride in doing so, but this display oi learning is somewhat tedious to the present-day reader, and interferes with the continuity ol the argument. He errs also on the side of completeness by arraying too many arguments in support oi his cause. Some ol them will not bear close examina- tion, and a elever opponent would have been able to make a specious case against him by directing the attention ot the court to arguments oi this sort.
